title: Elastic photon scattering between 9.5 and 12 MeV in Pb-208 and Pb-206.

x4freetext: Elastic photon scattering between 9.5 and 12  MeV  in
Pb-208 and Pb-206.

x4freetext: Illinois     microtron     using     a
superconducting linac (MUSL-2).
The detector was cylindrical and was about 15
cm in diameter and 23 cm deep.
Direct measurements  of  cross  section  values   for
coincidence counts between the tagged electrons from
microtron and the scattering gamma-quanta detector.
The statistical errors are presented only.
The  systematic   uncertainties   were
estimated  to  be  probably  less than 10%.  For the
smallest measured cross sections (i.e.,  equal to or
less   than   0.03   mb/sr)   there  are  additional
uncertainties caused by the difficulty of separating
reliably   the  elastic  scattering  peak  from  the
background in the gamma-ray spectrum  measured  with
the  NaI photon detector.  The data points below 9.7
MeV for Pb-208 and below 10 MeV for enriched  Pb-206
target  might,  therefore,  have  larger  systematic
errors.
Corrections for  geometric factors and for the atomic
absorption  of  photons  in  the  targets  may  have
contributed an uncertainty of 5% or less.
The elastic  photon  scattering  cross  sections   of
Pb-208  and Pb-206 were measured at 90 and 135 degr.
in the energy range from 9.5 to 12 MeV with a tagged
photon  beam  whose  energy spread was about 125 keV
The Pb-206 cross section  rises  monotonically  with
energy,  and  is  consistent  with  a  total  photon
interaction cross section  which  has  a  Lorentzian
energy  dependence  with a peak cross section of 650
mb at 13.6 MeV and a width about 3.8 MeV. The Pb-208
scattering  cross  section  is  larger  and has some
rapid variations with  energy;  there  is  a  narrow
extra  peak  near  10.04  MeV  and  there are abrupt
increases in the cross section just below  10.6  and
11.3  MeV.  The  relative scattering observed at the
two angles indicates that  all  of  the  scattering,
including  the  rapid  variations  with  energy,  is
dominated by dipole interactions.

x4freetext: Once  the  dominance of E1 processes has been
established,  the measured  scattering  differential
cross  section at 90 degrees can be converted to the
scattering  cross  section  integrated  over   angle
sig(Eg)   which   for  E1  scattering  is  given  by
equation:
sig(Eg) = 16.76(d-sig/d-omega(E,90-degrees)).
